After this construction, points $A,$ $B,$ $C,$ and $D$ are erased.  You only know the locations of points $A',$ $B',$ $C'$ and $D',$ and want to reconstruct quadrilateral $ABCD.$

There exist real numbers $p,$ $q,$ $r,$ and $s$ such that
\[\overrightarrow{A} = p \overrightarrow{A'} + q \overrightarrow{B'} + r \overrightarrow{C'} + s \overrightarrow{D'}.\]Enter the ordered quadruple $(p,q,r,s).$

solution:
We perform the polynomial division: \[
\begin{array}{c|cc cc}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{5x} & +4 \\
\cline{2-5}
2x^2-3x+1 & 10x^3&-7x^2&+ax&+6   \\
\multicolumn{2}{r}{-10x^3} & +15x^2 & -5x \\
\cline{2-4}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{0} & 8x^2 & (a-5)x & 6 \\
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & -8x^2 & +12x & -4 \\
\cline{3-5}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & 0 & (a-5+12)x & 2 \\
\end{array}
\]The remainder will be constant if and only if $a-5+12=0.$ So $a = \boxed{-7}.$

When we are subtracting, we want to subtract a smaller number from a bigger number. We can pull out a negative sign in order to accomplish this:  \[ 35_8-74_8 = -(74_8 - 35_8). \]Now, we can line in the numbers and subtract just as we do in base 10.  For example, when we borrow from the $8^1$s place, the digit 1 in the units place becomes $4+8=12$, while the digit in the $8^1$s place decreases by 1. Continuing in this way, we find $$\begin{array}{c@{}c@{}c@{}c}
& & \cancelto{6}{7} & \cancelto{12}{4}_8 \\
& - & 3 & 5_8 \\
\cline{2-4}
& & 3 & 7_8 \\
\end{array}$$Therefore, $35_8-74_8 = -(74_8 - 35_8) = \boxed{-37_8}$.

